  "prompt": "Is \"A Modest Proposal\" a parody?",
  "response": "Yes, \"A Modest Proposal\" is often considered a parody, as well as a satirical work. Written by Jonathan Swift in 1729, it employs satire to criticize British policy towards the Irish. Swift mockingly proposes that impoverished Irish might ease their economic troubles by selling their children as food to rich gentlemen and ladies. The outrageous nature of the suggestion parodies cold and calculative economic proposals that ignore human suffering, highlighting the indifference of the British rulers towards the plight of the Irish people.",
